XXXIV. TO HIMSELF

Parcus deorum cultor et infrequens

ISCIPLE of a mad philosophy, I am a rare, neglectful worshipper In the Gods' temples ; conscious that Ι err, Ι must shift sails, my course retraced shall be:

For Jupiter, -— whose wont it is to sunder With his forked fire the sky that tempests shroud, — Through the pure air serene, without a cloud,

Has driven his chariot swift, and Steeds of munder, —-

By which the inert earth and running rivers, — By which the Styx and Taenarus’ horrid seat, — The gate of hell, — with strange pulsations beat,

And the far Atlantean summit shivers. 60
